1958) / rBrewer, John Mason -- tThe Man and His Son (1962) / rSaucier, Corinne -- tThe Magician and His Disciple (1997) / rRamanujan, A. K. -- tPart III. Krabat Tales -- tAbout an Evil Man in Groß-Särchen (1837) / rHaupt, Joachim Leopold -- tKrabat: A Legend from Folklore (1858) / rHornig, Michael -- tKrabat (1865) / rKubasch, Georg Gustav -- tThe Sorcerer's Apprentice, I (1880; Recorded by Hendrich Jordan) / rVeckenstedt, Edmund -- tThe Sorcerer's Apprentice, II (1880; Recorded by Alexander von Rabenau) / rVeckenstedt, Edmund -- tThe Story about Krabat (1885) / rGoltsch, Johann -- tThe Wendish Faust Legend (1900) / rPilk, Georg -- tKrabat (1959) / rSlizinski, Jerzy -- tBiographies of Authors, Editors, Collectors, and Translators -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tSelected and Chronological List of Sorcerer's Apprentice Tales -- tIndex  aA diverse new anthology that traces the meaning and magic of the sorcerer's apprentice tale throughout history"The Sorcerer's Apprentice" might conjure up images of Mickey Mouse from the Disney film Fantasia, or of Harry Potter. As this anthology reveals, however, "sorcerer's apprentice" tales-in which a young person rebels against, or complies with, an authority who holds the keys to magical powers-have been told through the centuries, in many languages and cultures, from classical times to today. This unique and beautifully illustrated book brings together more than fifty sorcerer's apprentice stories by a plethora of writers, including Ovid, Sir Walter Scott, and the Brothers Grimm. From Goethe's "The Pupil in Magic" to A. K. Ramanujan's "The Guru and His Disciple," this expansive collection presents variations of a classic passed down through countries and eras.Readers enter worlds where household objects are brought to life and shape-shifting occurs from human to animal and back again. We meet two types of apprentice: "The Humiliated Apprentice," a foolish bumbler who wields magic ineffectively and promotes obedience to authority; and "The Rebellious Apprentice" who, through ambition and transformative skills, promotes empowerment and self-awareness. In an extensive introduction, esteemed fairy-tale scholar Jack Zipes discusses the significance and meaning of the apprentice stories, the contradictions in popular retellings, and the importance of magic as a tool of resistance against figures who abuse their authority. Twenty specially commissioned black-and-white illustrations by noted artist Natalie Frank bring the stories to visual life.The Sorcerer's Apprentice enlightens and entertains readers with enduring, spellbinding tales of sorcery that have been with us through the ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh1 aFrank, Natalie.1 aZipes, Jack, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400885633zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400885633.jpg  a978-3-11-054332-2  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN